# Will LLMs Alone Take Us To AGI

*Note: Whether you agree with this article or not, I am passionate about learning and would appreciate feedback. Please leave some recommended readings (papers, books, textbooks) that helped you to learn which I could use to broaden my perspective.*

**Author: Adit Rada**
**Date: Jul 9, 2024**

Ever since ChatGPT’s release in late 2022, LLMs have taken the world by storm and have captured people’s imaginations. For those of us monitoring the progress in Natural Language Processing, the dramatic improvement since the Transformers paper from 2017 \[[1](https://arxiv.org/abs/1706.03762)\] has been equally impressive. The rapid improvements in successive generations from GPT-1 all the way to GPT-4 has been awe-inspiring to say the least. All this has led some to believe that Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) is just a matter of years away \[[2](https://www.noemamag.com/artificial-general-intelligence-is-already-here/)\] \[[3](https://situational-awareness.ai/)\] \[[4](https://www.metaculus.com/questions/5121/date-of-artificial-general-intelligence/)\]. Wait a minute, what is AGI anyway?

# AGI

How to define AGI is another thorny issue \[[5](https://arxiv.org/abs/2311.02462)\] that warrants another blog post, and is out of scope for this one. For now, we will adopt the following definition: AGI is a computing-system that is capable of performing most, if not all, jobs that humans can do. The key word here is *”general”*, the system need not know how to do every single task at the same time, only that it is *general* enough to be able to learn to do every task.

AGI is *the* holy grail. Demis Hassabis, DeepMind’s co-founder, famously says “solve intelligence, and then use that to solve everything else” \[[6](https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/feb/16/demis-hassabis-artificial-intelligence-deepmind-alphago)\]. And that “everything else” includes energy, nuclear fusion, climate change, diseases, cancer, income inequality, social organizations, spreading Earth-based life across the Universe; you get the point \- literally everything\! Sidebar: I am personally most excited about learning about our own minds, about human intelligence, about human behavior, about *understanding intelligence.* I believe we can push the boundaries of our understanding of intelligence on the path to AGI.

# LLMs to AGI?

Now that we roughly know what AGI is, can LLMs get us there as some believe? Current generation LLMs (Gemini 1.5, GPT-4, Claude-3) are very impressive\! They show broad generality across a wide array of tasks \- they can talk about psychology, coding, poetry, history, biology, and much more. What’s most astounding is that simply scaling up LLMs \- in terms of parameters, compute, and data \- has led to emergent abilities \[[7](https://arxiv.org/abs/2206.07682)\]: i.e. the ability is not present in smaller models but is present in larger models. Indeed, the architectural differences between GPT-1 and GPT-3 are minimal, at the heart is the Transformer block. Each successive generation of GPT, is just a bigger and grander version of the previous one, trained on more data and more compute. This has led some people in the industry to believe that scaling LLMs may be all that is needed to achieve AGI \[[8](https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.12712)\]. Part of Nvidia skyrocketing to be the most valuable company is due to the belief that throwing more compute at LLMs will lead to more intelligence; this has led companies to hoard GPUs in anticipation of ever-larger models.

But, are LLMs truly intelligent in the way animals on Earth are?

Let’s step back and talk about intelligence. Francois Chollet (the author of Keras) [says](https://x.com/fchollet/status/1727855591383810378) that “intelligence is about generating adequate behavior in the presence of high uncertainty and constant change”. What makes “intelligence” intelligent is its ability to adapt to changing environments to survive. This is why intelligence is evolutionarily beneficial. Earth, and its environment, has been constantly changing since its inception 3.8 BYA. Adapting to this constant change requires intelligent animals that can *learn* and produce appropriate behavior to survive in that given environment. If the environment was static, and never changed, evolution would have simply *hardcoded* all the rules required to survive. But evolution did not do that (for our lineage at least), it instead gave animals the ability to *learn* the rules as required.

For example, if a *new* predator appears in the environment, then individuals capable of learning to avoid the predator will be more successful than individuals who cannot learn. In effect, the ability to learn allows an individual to perform a small local search during its lifetime to maximize its fitness. In contrast, non-learning individuals whose fitness is fully determined by their genetic makeup will operate at a relative disadvantage.

By this definition of intelligence, current-generation LLMs are not intelligent in the way we are, they can’t learn *new* rules, and adapt. Best evidence of this is their horrible performance on the quite simple ARC test \[[9](https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.01547)\].

So what then are LLMs? One can think of LLMs as knowledge databases or indexes that we can retrieve information from using natural language instead of SQL queries. By being trained on all of the web, LLMs are compressing that information and storing it for later retrieval via natural language. They are the next generation of “classical” relational and NoSQL databases. This is not to say the LLMs are not impressive; as Ilya Sutskever says, to predict the next token accurately, the model should understand a great deal about the world \[[10](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yf1o0TQzry8)\]. But that in itself does not mean they are intelligent. Instead, they are very good at building an accurate model of the statistical distribution of language.

# The components of intelligence

The human brain is the only data point we have on how to achieve human-level intelligence. So, let’s look into this single data point and see what it's made of.

In his excellent book, *A Brief History of Intelligence* \[[11](https://books.google.ca/books/about/A_Brief_History_of_Intelligence.html?id=tymCEA)\], Max Bennet outlines five breakthroughs that led to the human brain:

1) **Steering in bilaterians**: 600 MYA, this was the first brain.  
2) **Reinforcing in vertebrates**: 500 MYA, this was the brain learning by doing.  
3) **Simulating in mammals**: 200 MYA, this was the brain learning by imagining.  
4) **Mentalizing in primates**: 15 MYA, this was the brain learning from the actions of others.  
5) **Speaking in humans**: 100 KYA, this was the brain learning from the imaginations of others.

As we can see already, there are aspects of human intelligence that emerged way before language, and these are the aspects that LLMs mostly come up short on.

### Reinforcing

A differentiating factor of vertebrates is that they can learn by doing. By the way, this was also the first time in history the brain incorporated learning, moving away from hardcoded rules. This component of intelligence \- reinforcing \- is captured by the famous **Law of Effect** introduced by Edward Thorndike in 1898\. The law says that: “*Responses that produce a satisfying effect in a particular situation become more likely to occur again in that situation, and responses that produce a discomforting effect become less likely to occur again in that situation”.*

As an example, take a dog being trained with clicker training.  At first, the dog might try various actions for the click. However, upon clicking and rewarding the desired behavior (like sitting), the dog learns that sitting leads to the positive outcome and strengthens that association, making it more likely to sit again in the future.

This is also known as **Reinforcement Learning** (RL). The part of the brain that is most responsible for implementing this algorithm is the *basal ganglia.* RL is something that may be necessary in an AGI system but is missing in current generation LLMs.

#### Language Models and Reinforcing

Yes, I agree there is RL in LLMs: Reinforcement Learning with Human Feedback (RLHF) has proven to be an incredibly effective technique in aligning LLMs. With RLHF, LLMs are able to incorporate external feedback to change their answers. But this type of RL is still a far cry from the flexibility with which animal species employ reinforcement learning.

When I say LLMs are missing RL, I mean the following:

* They are not “agentic” in the way RL agents are. They can’t learn in a completely *online and incremental* fashion the way an animal species can. Their training has to be frozen, and then deployed, there is no possibility for **continual learning**.  
* **Catastrophic forgetting**: LLMs (or any Neural Network for that matter) are susceptible to catastrophic forgetting \[[12](https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.08747)\], which is the tendency to abruptly and drastically forget previously learned information upon learning new information. This means that they can’t continuously learn as they interact with the world (currently, by chatting with users), something vertebrates can effortlessly do. “Train a fish to escape from a net through a small escape hatch, leave the fish alone for an entire year, and then test it again. During this long stretch of time, its brain will have received a constant stream of patterns, learning continually to recognize new smells, sights, and sounds. And yet, when you place the fish back in the same net an entire year later, it will remember how to get out with almost the same speed and accuracy as it did the year before.” \[[11](https://books.google.ca/books/about/A_Brief_History_of_Intelligence.html?id=tymCEA)\]

RL (learning by doing), as evidenced by its importance in animals, will be a key feature of an AGI system, but current LLMs don’t have it.

### Simulating

Simulating emerged in mammals 500 MYA building on top of reinforcing machinery from the vertebrates. The sensory *neocortex* evolved, which created a simulation of the external  
world (a world model). The agranular prefrontal cortex evolved, which created a simulation of an animal’s own movements and internal states (a self model). Together, they enabled early  
mammals to pause and simulate aspects of the world that were not currently being experienced—in other words, model-based reinforcement learning.

David Redish, in a groundbreaking study, recorded neural activity of rats as they went through a maze. He found that rats actually simulated future paths when they reached forks in the road. They were literally playing out (like Monte-Carlo Tree Search) future actions by using their inner world model \[[13](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24908102/)\].

The neocortex, which enabled simulating, gifted mammals with:

* **Learning by imagining**, instead of just learning by doing as in vertebrates. For example, using its imagination, a squirrel can plan out several paths to get to the burrow, and then choose the path which is least risky.  
* **Counterfactual learning**, which enables mammals to learn about causal relationships. For example, “I went right over here yesterday and almost got eaten by a T-rex, I’ll go left instead”. This requires simulating past events using your world model, and learning from the imagination.  
* **Episodic memory**, which allowed mammals to recall past events and actions, and use these recollections to adjust their behavior. For example, “in my world model, I saw a snake up that tree yesterday, so I’ll avoid that tree today”.  
* **Fine movements**, the motor cortex enables mammals to plan and simulate their movements. Think of the difference between the refined movements of a mammal like a rat and the rough movements of a vertebrate like a crocodile. (By the way, you used your neocortex to *imagine/simulate* those two scenes).

#### Language Models and Simulating

Pausing and thinking about future actions is something LLMs just can’t do. The best evidence for this is that they spend an equal amount of compute for each output token regardless of the complexity of the problem. As another example, a study found that ChatGPT excelled at solving coding problems from LeetCode that existed before its 2021 training data cutoff. However, its performance significantly declined when faced with even easy problems added after 2021, often failing to understand the questions. \[[17](https://spectrum.ieee.org/chatgpt-for-coding)\].

Thus, this major intellectual feat that can be done by simple rat brains can’t be done by LLMs that cost hundreds of millions of dollars. This is also the reason, Yann LeCun says we should “abandon LLMs” \[[14](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5t1vTLU7s40)\] if we ever want to achieve AGI. He argues that before we have human-like intelligence, we will need to have rat-like intelligence.

In LeCun’s words: “We humans give way too much importance to language and symbols as the substrate of intelligence. Primates, dogs, cats, crows, parrots, octopi, and many other animals don’t have human-like languages, yet exhibit intelligent behavior beyond that of our best AI systems. What they do have is an ability to learn powerful “world models” that allow them to predict the consequences of their actions and to search for and plan actions to achieve a goal. The ability to learn such world models is what’s missing from AI systems today”.

### Mentalizing

Mentalizing emerged 15 MYA in early primates. Mentalizing is the ability to understand the mental state of oneself or others. The brain regions that were most responsible for this ability are the granular prefrontal cortex (gPFC), superior temporal sulcus (STS) and the temporoparietal junction (TPJ). 

Mentalizing gifted primates with:

* **Theory of Mind (ToM)**: inferring intent and knowledge of others. For example, researchers observed a chimp who found hidden food. Another chimp, unaware of the hidden food, approached. The first chimp then made a specific "deception call" typically used to lure others away from a food source. This suggests the first chimp understood the second chimp didn't know about the food and aimed to manipulate its behavior.  
* **Imitation learning**: learning by observing the actions of others. For example, a young gorilla learning to make a termite fishing tool by watching her mother  
* **Anticipating future needs**: taking actions now to satisfy a need of the future. For example, going grocery shopping even if you are not hungry now, carrying a jacket even if you are not currently cold. One can think of this as theory of mind *for your own mind*. The same machinery that is used to do theory of mind for other minds, is also used for your own mind, to infer your own future state of mind.

Consciousness is another thorny issue that sparks wild debates. But, a definition of consciousness that is somewhat accepted is that consciousness is self-awareness, i.e. thinking about your own mind; thinking about thinking. By this definition, consciousness first emerged in primates and was passed down to humans.

#### Language Models and Mentalizing

LLMs can do some theory of mind tasks. But their answers for these tasks are more like retrieving information from a database. They don’t seem to actively reason, infer the intent of others and model another mind. As we saw above, theory of mind for other minds *and* theory of mind for your own mind (consciousness) use the same hardware and algorithms. Therefore, doing one means the other just happens. Therefore, if LLMs can indeed do theory of mind for others, they must also be able to do theory of mind for themselves, and hence are conscious. However, any neuroscientist or AI researcher will say LLMs are not conscious (can’t do theory of mind for their own mind), so it must be that they can’t do theory of mind for other minds. So all the ToM tasks they seem to pass are just regurgitations of patterns they have already seen in their training data.

LLMs not having mentalizing capability is also the reason we have to carefully prompt engineer them, since they can not infer our intent or knowledge. If LLMs had the capability of theory of mind, prompt engineering would become less crucial. They would be able to grasp the nuances and underlying assumptions in a prompt and provide responses that accurately reflect the user's intent.

As we can see, a majority of intellectual feats that we normally associate with humans actually came way before us. The incredible progress in neuroscience over the last 100 years has led to a greater understanding of our brain, and Homo Sapiens can’t solely take credit for these intellectual feats.

### Speaking

Sometime between 1 MYA and 100 KYA came language, and with it our genus transformed from irrelevance in the African Savannah to being on top of the food chain. Almost all aspects of intelligence we associate with humans came before us, and language is just the icing on top.

So what then is so special about language that allowed us to conquer Earth? Language gave us the gift of being able to share our internal models/simulations/thoughts with others. This allowed us to learn from the imaginations of others. For example, without language there is no way for human A to tell human B there is a lion on the other side of the hill, i.e. human B can’t learn from the internal model of human A. Language allowed us to communicate learnings (like building tools) across generations. This allowed us to build on top of the ideas of the previous generation, rather than reinventing the wheel from scratch. This compounding effect led to an exponential increase in the sophistication of ideas and tools. Language is what allows us to *stand on the shoulders of giants*.

Take ChatGPT for example, it was built on top of Transformers, which improved on RNNs, which improved on FFNNs, which was possible because of backpropagation, operating systems, databases, computer networking, transistors, electricity and so on. So, it is this cumulative effect of language that allowed us to conquer Earth.

Language is not the cause for sophisticated thinking of humans, instead it is merely a reflection of the sophisticated thinking of humans. Another evidence for this is that the language-network and the thought-network in the brain are distinct. Damage to the language network does not diminish the ability to simulate/imagine, think, and reason. An intact language network does not mean intact thinking, and vice versa.

![][image1]  
*Reproduced from Evelina Fedorenko et al. \[[15](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-07522-w)\]*

Fedorenko, et al. \[[15](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-07522-w)\] bring together decades of research that shows language is optimized to be a communication protocol rather than a substrate for thinking. The evidence that supports this claim are:

* **Phonetic space**: In all languages, the sounds of words are spread out so that they can be robust to noise, which makes sense only if we view language as being used as a communication protocol, rather than as a tool for thought.  
* **Energy efficiency:** Common words (“the”, “an”, e.t.c.) are short, which makes them more energy efficient to produce, and easy to learn. This is a hallmark of any good communication protocol, common patterns should be short and easy to produce.  
* **Communication efficiency:** Languages balance how complex words are to learn and remember (complexity) with how clearly they convey specific meanings (informativeness). This "informativeness-complexity trade-off" explains why languages like English have terms like "maternal grandmother" for precise relationships, but also simpler terms like "brother" for broader categories. This efficiency is seen in color terms, seasons, and grammar as well. This efficiency is another sign that language is optimized to be a communication protocol.  
* **Syntactic efficiency:** Languages favor sentence structures that minimize the "distance" between related words. Imagine "Lana ate five apples." "Five" modifies "apples," but "Lana" doesn't relate directly. Studies show that longer distances make sentences harder to understand. This pressure to be efficient explains why languages tend to place related words close together.  
* **Prevalence of ambiguity**: many words have multiple meanings. Since our thoughts don’t seem ambiguous, this is clear proof that language is not used for or enables thought. On the other hand, the existence of ambiguity makes sense if language is used as a communication protocol \- it enables the reuse of words, making the protocol easy to learn and fit in the brain.

These properties of human languages make them easy to produce, easy to learn and understand, concise and efficient to use, and robust to noise. Basically, they make language a very good communication protocol.

Language gifted us with a protocol to communicate our internal models/simulations to others. This communication allowed us to break the shackles with biological evolution, and allowed us to have idea evolution \[[16](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sapiens:_A_Brief_History_of_Humankind)\]. And this idea evolution allowed us to build better tools, cultures, norms, and societies. So, yes language is a big deal\! But we must not fall into the trap that because it is a big deal, that it is the only deal. Language is merely the icing on top of the cake. We just went through solid evidence that many of the intellectual feats we associate with humans actually came way before us.

#### Language Models and Language

Language models are thus modeling a communication protocol. They are trying to decode our internal world and self models by deciphering a protocol that we use to *communicate* about our internal world and self models. And this is the fundamental difference between language models and intelligence. They have missing components that even fish, cats, and bonobos have. That’s why Yann LeCun says “*Let’s start with Artificial Rat–level intelligence (ARI), then move on to Artificial Cat–level intelligence (ACI), and so on to Artificial Human–level Intelligence (AHI).”*

As we scale up language models, we are essentially just building better and better databases (or knowledge repositories). They will be impressively good, but they will also lack something unique and essential to animal intelligence. This would have been perfectly fine had the world remained static. However, this is not the case. Intelligence evolved in the first place so that life can adapt to a dynamic and changing world; if the world was static, hardcoded rules in our DNA would have been enough to survive. Language models trained today would have been useless 10,000 years ago, and will be useless 10,000 years from now, because the world would be different in both cases.

# Conclusion \- where does this leave us?

The recent remarkable progress of LLMs has forced us to reflect on the nature of intelligence and pushed our understanding of the brain \- the most complex thing we know in the Universe \- to a greater depth.

LLMs are one of the most (if not the most) impressive pieces of tech we have ever built (as of July 2024). They have been unreasonably effective in our attempts to model language. All kinds of cool and useful products will be built on top of them \- my favorite has been coding assistants. Engineers who use LLMs will be more productive as they have a powerful database to access information from in a more intuitive way. This increased productivity, and wider access to knowledge may lead to more discoveries, innovation and economic growth.

So, will LLMs alone take us to AGI? Based on my *current* knowledge and experience, I am skeptical that LLMs alone will lead to AGI. They may be a part of a future AGI system, but I doubt that they will be *the* AGI system.

Maybe I am wrong, maybe there are multiple paths to human-level intelligence, and scaling up LLMs may eventually lead to AGI. However, the path that LLMs have taken is drastically different from the path we took.
